    "content": "<h2>1. Conditional Types</h2>\n<p>Conditional types allow you to create types that depend on other types. They follow the same syntax as ternary operators in JavaScript: <code>T extends U ? X : Y</code>.</p>\n<h3>Example: Extracting Return Types</h3>\n<p>One common use case is extracting the return type of a function. TypeScript provides a built-in <code>ReturnType&#x3C;T></code> utility, but let's see how we could implement it ourselves using conditional types.</p>\n<figure data-rehype-pretty-code-figure=\"\"><pre style=\"--shiki-light:#24292eff;--shiki-dark:#F8F8F2;--shiki-light-bg:#ffffff;--shiki-dark-bg:#282A36\" tabindex=\"0\" data-language=\"typescript\" data-theme=\"min-light dracula\"><code data-language=\"typescript\" data-theme=\"min-light dracula\" style=\"display: grid;\"><span data-line=\"\"><span style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#FF79C6\">type</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#6F42C1;--shiki-light-font-style:inherit;--shiki-dark:#8BE9FD;--shiki-dark-font-style:italic\"> MyReturnType</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#24292EFF;--shiki-dark:#F8F8F2\">&#x3C;</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#6F42C1;--shiki-light-font-style:inherit;--shiki-dark:#FFB86C;--shiki-dark-font-style:italic\">T</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#24292EFF;--shiki-dark:#F8F8F2\">> </span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#FF79C6\">=</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#6F42C1;--shiki-light-font-style:inherit;--shiki-dark:#8BE9FD;--shiki-dark-font-style:italic\"> T</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#FF79C6\"> extends</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#24292EFF;--shiki-dark:#F8F8F2\"> (</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#FF79C6\">...</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#24292EFF;--shiki-light-font-style:inherit;--shiki-dark:#FFB86C;--shiki-dark-font-style:italic\">args</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#FF79C6\">:</span><span style=\"--shiki-light:#1976D2;--shiki-light-font-style:inhe